‘Unstacking’ Bars

lindbrook

2016-09-25

Overview

In his map of the 1854 cholera outbreak in London, John Snow used stacks of bars to represent the number of fatalities at an address: for example, a location with one fatality is represented by a single, horizontal bar; a location with five is represented by five horizontally stacked bars:1

In 1992, Rusty Dodson and Waldo Tobler digitized the map. Each bar and water pump was given a unique x-y coordinate. Each road was translated into a set of straight line segments, defined by their endpoints. While the original data are no longer available,2 they are included in Michael Friendly’s HistData R package. The data are plotted below:

Despite their appeal, I would argue that stacks are visually and computationally problematic. The reason? Not all bars are created equal. Even though they are identical in terms of their appearance and the only thing that seems to distinguish them is their position on the map, bars actually play two different roles. Sometimes a bar represent the location of a fatality, sometimes it doesn’t. Standalone bars (i.e., a stack with a one bar or an addresses with one fatality), or of the bar at the base of a stack do. Bars above the base case do not: their only purpose is to create the visual stacking effect.

While this duality is not inherently problematic, it becomes problematic in a map. Because a map is a visual device that illustrates spatial relationships, it’s natural to assume that the positions of all elements (e.g., bars) represent actual physical locations. So when we violate this principle, we undermine our visual interpretation of the map and handicap our attempt to analyze the data in the map. This is particularly true when 44% (257/578) of bars in Snow’s map fall into this geographically uninformative category.

To address these problems, I “unstack” Dodson and Tobler’s data. I do so in two different data sets. The first, fatalities.unstacked, “unstacks” the data so that all cases in a stack (at the same “address”) are given the same x-y coordinate. The second, unstacked.address, “unstacks” the data by changing the unit of observation from the case to the stack (or “address”). Each “address” is a single observation with a single x-y coordinate, and the number of cases at that location becomes an attribute of the “address”.

Virtues of “unstacking”

To illustrate the problems with “stacked” data and the virtues of “unstacked” data, consider two examples.

Kernel density contours

The first example applies applies bivariate kernel density contours, of varying bandwidth, to “stacked” and “unstacked” data. The plots illustrate the spatial distribution or topography of fatalities, and provides a way to estimate the epicenter, if not the source, of the outbreak.

With the “stacked” data, fatalities, the contours and epicenter are further south than we might expect given that the Broad Street pump (blue triangle) is the recognized source of the outbreak. The problem is that the “vertical” stack of 18 cases (west of the pump at 38 Broad Street) and the “horizontal” stack of 5 cases (south of the pump at 10 Cambridge Street) pull the fit downward, in a southerly direction.

With fatalities.unstacked, the contours and epicenter are located further north, nearer to both the pump and Broad Street:

An alternative approach to “stacks”

The second example uses unstacked.address to create an alternative to “stacked” bars based on proportionately sized points. Each address is represented by a square whose size is determined by the number of fatalities and whose location is represented by a point at its center.3

“Unstacking” via classification

This section discusses the specifics of how I “unstacked” the data. The main roadblock that makes “unstacking” difficult is that there is no notion of an “address”. Bars are merely points and streets are merely line segments.4 Nothing links the points to segments. And nothing connects one bar in a stack to another. All elements exist independently of one another. The only reason why the map “works” is that the fatalities and roads data have overlapping x-y coordinates.

Therefore, to “unstack” the data , we need match each bar to a specific road (segment) and to match each bar to a specific stack. To accomplish these tasks, I employ two different classifications methods.

Orthogonal projection

The first method works by orthogonal projection. For each bar, the algorithm draws a series of lines that pass through that bar and that are orthogonal to each nearby road segment.5 If a projected line intersects or bisects a road segment, it becomes a candidate for the bar’s home segment. If there’s more than one candidate, the algorithm chooses the segment that is “closest” to the bar: this will be the segment with the shortest orthogonal projector.

To illustrate, consider the stylized example in the figure below. For case 12, there are three possible “home” road segments: the solid blue, red and green segments.

We consider them because at least one of their endpoints fall within 50 meters, or on the map’s nominal scale a distance of 0.5, of case 12’s position. Of the three, only red and green are viewed as candidates. The problem with blue is that the orthogonal projection from case 12 (the blue arrow) does not intersect the solid blue segment. Of the two candidates, red is chosen because it is closer to case 12 than green: the red arrow is shorter than the green one.

This procedure correctly classifies 515 of 578 of the cases, an error rate of 10.9%. Errors occur due to ambiguities surrounding a case’s “home” segment. Unlike Snow’s map where a bar’s “horizontal” orientation indicates its “home” segment, Dodson and Tobler only record a case’s x-y coordinates. This can lead to problems at street intersections, where a point may be closer to the “wrong” segment, and at addresses with many cases.6 The problem with multiple cases is that stacking pushes cases away from the “home” segment. Consider the figure below. Even though visual inspection (the alignment of the stack) should lead us to choose black, the algorithm chooses red. The reason for the error is that stacking pushes the case so far from black that it lies beyond consideration.7 With stacks, this kind of misclassification is always a potential threat.

All errors were corrected by manually recoding cases.

Cluster analysis

To match a bar to a stack, I use hierarchical cluster analysis.8 To make this task easier, instead of its x-y coordinates I use a bar’s orthogonal coordinates. That is, I use the point where the the orthogonal projection from the bar intersects the road segment. Doing so reduces the dimensionality of the problem: the algorithm only needs to compare positions of points along a line.

The figure below illustrates this approach. Using a case’s x-y coordinates, the graph plots the case’s numeric ID and draws the corresponding orthogonal projector to Broad Street. Matching a bar to a stack, which is equivalent to identifying a stack, means identifying distinct clusters of points along the road segment. For the case at hand, visual inspection leads us to expect that we should find 8 different clusters along this segment of Broad Street (4 on the north side, 4 on the south side).9

This can be confirmed by examining Snow’s map10:

The fly in the ointment is that addresses directly opposite one another will have “identical” orthogonal points and will appear to belong to the same “address”. A simple solution to distinguish clusters on one side of the street from those on the other is to compute the sign of the arithmetic difference between a case’s x-y coordinate and its orthogonal coordinate. For example, consider cases 321 and 239. They lie on opposite sides of Broad Street. In the figure below, 321’s coordinates are shown in blue while 239’s are shown in red. When we take the signs of the differences, we get (-, +) for 321 and (+, -) for 239. This distinguishes cases on the north side from those on the south side.

In general, for roads with positive slopes (e.g., Broad Street), the differences for cases on the north/west side will be (-, +) while those on the south/east side will be (+, -); for roads with negative slopes (e.g., Cambridge Street), the differences for cases on the north/east side will be (-, -) while those on the south/west side will be (+, +).11

With this information, I can use cluster analysis to identify stacks, or “addresses”, on each side of a candidate road segment. Since we expect the distances between cases in a stack or “address” to be small, I use an arbitrarily low but reasonable cutoff “height” of 0.05. The two dendrograms below represent the North and South sides of Broad Street. We can see that this procedure correctly classifies the 8 different groups or stacks that can be seen in the figure above and that can be verified by looking at Snow’s map.

In Snow’s map, Portland Mews is a large yard or square. In Dodson and Tobler, Portland Mews simply a set of line segments, which possibly corresponds to the roadway through the location. As a result, given the orientation of the cases of Snow’s map and location of the cases in Dodson and Tobler, these three cases will appear to belong to a single cluster instead of two different ones.   9. What makes this approach feasible is that, by design, its “vertical” dispersion, the spread of x-y points along the orthogonal axis, is much greater than its “horizontal” dispersion, the spread of orthogonal points along the road’s line segment. In an ideal world, the “horizontal” dispersion would be zero and all points in a stack would be perfectly aligned. In practice, this is not the case.↩

  10. In Snow’s map, one can see 5 addresses on the north side of the block of Broad Street between Dufours Place and Poland Street (the road running north-south just visible on the east or left side of the graph) but only 4 of those addresses fall on the street segment in Dodson and Tobler. The reason for the apparent discrepancy is that intersections with other streets, regardless of which side of the road they may fall, define the end points of road segments. This is why the south side of this segment of Broad Street only includes 4 addresses: the endpoints are defined by Dufours Place on the left (west) and Cambridge Street on the right (east).↩

  11. The two limiting cases occur when roads run either along the East-West axis (i.e., 0 degrees) or the North-South axis (i.e., 90 degrees). For the former, cases on the north side will be (0, +) while those on the south side will be (0, -); for the latter, cases on the east side will be (+, 0) while those on the west side will be (-, 0).↩
